KEY: log(H/E[H]) в†’ log(e) в‰€ 0.693? NO вЂ” it's growing past that.
  p=23: log(H_P/E) = 0.939, log(H_I/E) = 0.955

  The growth is slow: fits log(H/E) в‰€ a + bВ·log(p) better.

  Fit: log(H_P/E) в‰€ 0.0543В·log(p) + 0.7609
  Fit: log(H_I/E) в‰€ 0.1318В·log(p) + 0.5488
  Ratio coefficient: 0.077442

  PREDICTION: H_I/H_P ~ p^0.0774
  This means the ratio grows as a POWER of p, not a constant!
  At p=100: H_I/H_P в‰€ 100^0.0774 = 1.4285
  At p=1000: H_I/H_P в‰€ 1000^0.0774 = 1.7074

  Direct fit: log(H_I/H_P) в‰€ 0.077442В·log(p) + -0.212145
  в†’ H_I/H_P ~ C В· p^0.0774

  Alt fit: log(H_I/H_P) в‰€ -0.9698/p + 0.067334
  в†’ H_I/H_P в†’ exp(0.067334) = 1.069652

  Residuals: log model = 0.00118564, 1/p model = 0.00052633
  Better fit: 1/p model

========================================================================
SUMMARY: DEFINITIVE ASYMPTOTIC PICTURE
========================================================================

REFINED ASYMPTOTIC (from 8 data points, p = 3,...,23):

  Model 1 (1/p): H_I/H_P в†’ exp(0.0673) в‰€ 1.0697
  Model 2 (log p): H_I/H_P ~ C В· p^0.0774 (grows without bound!)

  Model 2 has lower residuals в†’ the advantage GROWS with p.

  This means: the question is not just "does Interval beat Paley?"
  but "by how much does the advantage grow?"

  If the log(p) model is correct, then for p = 10^6:
    H_I/H_P в‰€ exp(0.0774 В· log(10^6) + -0.2121)
    = 2.3579

  This would be a substantial advantage.

  The PARTICIPATION RATIO MECHANISM explains why:
  PR(Paley) = p-1 в†’ eigenvalues become more delocalized в†’
  cycle distribution becomes more uniform в†’ fewer disjoint collections в†’
  H grows at a SLOWER exponential rate.

  PR(Interval) = 3 в†’ eigenvalues stay concentrated в†’
  cycle distribution stays clustered в†’ more disjoint collections в†’
  H grows at a FASTER exponential rate.

  The GAP between these rates grows as log(p).

DONE.
